yuna: That night I sat with my notebook open for a long time without writing anything.
yuna: I kept thinking about what Baku said.
yuna: "You'll tell me eventually.".
yuna: Like it was already decided. Like she already knew she'd be here when I got around to it.
yuna: Nobody has ever assumed that about me before.
yuna: At the association, everything was conditional.
yuna: Your position, your assignments, the way people looked at you in the hallway — all of it contingent on your last performance.
yuna: One mistake and the whole thing recalibrated.
yuna: I knew that going in. I accepted it. I told myself that was just how things worked.
yuna: And then I made one mistake.
yuna: And they were right — that is how things worked. It worked exactly like that.
yuna: I keep telling myself I want to go back. And I do. I think I do.
yuna: But when I try to picture it —
yuna: — walking back into that building, sitting at that desk, being that version of myself again —
yuna: — what I feel isn't longing.
yuna: I don't know what it is.
yuna: So I do what I always do when things are unclear.
yuna: I open my notebook to a fresh page. Write it down. Make it concrete.
yuna: "Objective\: prove competence. Return to the association."
yuna: Two lines. Clear. Measurable.
yuna: That's enough for now.
yuna: (closes the notebook)
